# ctx.elapsed and dt

Two time values are available in update():

```
export function update(ctx, dt) {
  // ctx.elapsed — seconds since setup() was called
  // dt          — seconds since last frame (~0.016 at 60fps)
}
```

Use `ctx.elapsed` for position-based animations that need a consistent reference regardless of framerate:

```
mesh.position.y = Math.sin(ctx.elapsed) * 1.5;
```

Use `dt` to scale velocity-based changes so motion stays consistent at any frame rate:

```
mesh.rotation.y += 1.0 * dt;  // always 1 radian/sec
```

# Sine Wave Motion

Math.sin() produces smooth oscillation between −1 and 1:

```
// Simple Y bounce
mesh.position.y = Math.sin(ctx.elapsed) * amplitude;

// Phase-shift multiple objects
for (let i = 0; i < meshes.length; i++) {
  meshes[i].position.y =
    Math.sin(ctx.elapsed + i * 0.8) * 1.5;
}
```

Scale the frequency by multiplying elapsed:

```
Math.sin(ctx.elapsed * 2.0)  // 2x faster
Math.sin(ctx.elapsed * 0.5)  // half speed
```

Combine two sines at different frequencies for organic, non-repeating motion:

```
const x = Math.sin(t * 1.3) * 2;
const z = Math.sin(t * 0.7 + 1.2) * 2;
```

# Sawtooth Motion

The % operator creates a ramp that resets every N seconds:

```
// t cycles 0→1 every 2 seconds
const t = (ctx.elapsed % 2) / 2;

// Map to -1..1
mesh.position.x = t * 2 - 1;
```

This produces a linear sawtooth — useful for conveyor belts, ticking animations, or counters.

## Triangle Wave (Ping-Pong)

For a back-and-forth motion without the hard reset:

```
const t = (ctx.elapsed % 2) / 2;
// 0→1 in first half, 1→0 in second half
const ping = t < 0.5 ? t * 2 : (1 - t) * 2;
mesh.position.x = ping * 4 - 2;
```

# Easing Functions

Easing functions remap a 0→1 input to produce non-linear motion:

```
function easeInOut(t) {
  return t < 0.5
    ? 2 * t * t
    : -1 + (4 - 2 * t) * t;
}

// Drive with a sawtooth input
const t = (ctx.elapsed % 2) / 2;
mesh.position.y = easeInOut(t) * 3 - 1.5;
```

## Common Easing Types

```
// Ease In (slow start)
t * t

// Ease Out (slow end)
1 - (1 - t) * (1 - t)

// Cubic Ease In-Out
t < 0.5
  ? 4*t*t*t
  : 1 - Math.pow(-2*t+2, 3) / 2
```

# Lerp — Smooth Follow

Linear interpolation moves a value a fraction of the way toward a target each frame:

```
// current creeps toward target
current += (target - current) * 0.08;
```

The factor (0.08) controls speed — larger = snappier, smaller = smoother. Note: this is framerate-dependent; for consistent behavior use:

```
const k = 1 - Math.pow(0.01, dt);
current += (target - current) * k;
```

Three.js provides lerp on Vector3 and Color directly:

```
mesh.position.lerp(targetPos, 0.08);
mesh.material.color.lerp(targetColor, 0.05);
```
